<paragraph blockId="21.[132,775,1248,1430]" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">
ORIGINAL DATA. — A total of 
<specimenCount box="[440,574,1248,1272]" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" type="generic">41 specimens</specimenCount>
of this species were capture during our surveys, of which most were in the understory canopy of primary forest at an altitude of 
<quantity box="[553,619,1301,1325]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.3" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" unit="m" value="630.0">630 m</quantity>
a.s.l. (
<tableCitation box="[687,761,1301,1325]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="6.[134,145,230,248]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="TABLE 1. — Sampling stations, habitat sampled and species captured during our field surveys (2016-2018). Abbreviations: A, above slow-flowing steam, B, cultivated farm; C, fallow farmland; D, beside fruiting tree; E, cleared farmland; F, understory of Primary forest; G, ecotone forest/alpine grassland, H, cave; I, gap between trees; J, forest fragment; K, waterhole." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF4C665DD54639431C8FFF45FDEA411C" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" tableUuid="DF4C665DD54639431C8FFF45FDEA411C">Table 1</tableCitation>
). This corroborates the report by 
<bibRefCitation author="Fedden &amp; MacLeod" box="[445,720,1327,1351]" firstAuthor="Fedden" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" pagination="175 - 195" refId="ref25479" refString="FEDDEN M. O. &amp; MACLEOD H. L. 1986. - Bat research in western Cameroon in S. N. STUART (ed.), Conservation of Cameroon montane forest. Report of the ICBP Cameroon Montane Forest Survey November 1983 - April 1984. International Council for Bird Preservation, Cambridge: 175 - 195." type="book chapter" year="1986">Fedden &amp; MacLeod (1986)</bibRefCitation>
, who mostly recorded this species at low altitude. 
<bibRefCitation author="Eisentraut" box="[545,714,1354,1378]" firstAuthor="Eisentraut" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" refId="ref25058" refString="EISENTRAUT M. 1963. - Die Wirbeltiere des Kamerungebirges. Verlag Paul Parey, Hamburg, 353 p." type="book" year="1963">Eisentraut (1963)</bibRefCitation>
noted that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Noack" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[177,353,1380,1404]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ruber">
<emphasis box="[177,353,1380,1404]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">Hipposideros ruber</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabits lowland regions, but could extend into montane forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="502" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="21.[132,776,1454,1637]" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">
DIAGNOSIS. — The forearm measurement of these specimens are 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.125" metricValueMax="5.34" metricValueMin="4.91" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" unit="mm" value="51.25" valueMax="53.4" valueMin="49.1">49.1 to 53.4 mm</quantity>
(
<tableCitation box="[267,341,1481,1505]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="12.[134,145,220,238]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="TABLE 3. — External measurements of adult bats captured on Mount Cameroon. Measurements are given as mean ± standard deviation and range." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF4C665DD54C39491C8FFF7FFAB440D7" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" tableUuid="DF4C665DD54C39491C8FFF7FFAB440D7">Table 3</tableCitation>
). Other features stated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Happold" box="[607,769,1481,1505]" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" refId="ref25900" refString="HAPPOLD D. C. D. 1987. - The mammals of Nigeria. Clarendon Press. Oxford, 402 p. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0030605300027708" type="book" year="1987">Happold (1987)</bibRefCitation>
, such as the variable color phases ranging from orange-rufous to greyish-brown were present in these specimens. Also the ears are large and pointed and the antitragus is well developed. The species is distinguishable from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sundevall" baseAuthorityYear="1846" box="[334,507,1586,1610]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caffer">
<emphasis box="[334,507,1586,1610]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">Hipposideros caffer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the larger forearm length of above 
<quantity box="[220,292,1613,1637]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" unit="mm" value="50.0">50 mm</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Patterson &amp; Webala" box="[306,559,1613,1637]" firstAuthor="Patterson" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" pagination="1 - 160" refId="ref28708" refString="PATTERSON B. D &amp; WEBALA P. W. 2012. - Keys to the bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) of East Africa. Fieldiana: Life and Earth Sciences 6: 1 - 160. https: // doi. org / 10.3158 / 2158 - 5520 - 12.6.1" type="journal article" year="2012">Patterson &amp; Webala 2012</bibRefCitation>
) (
<tableCitation box="[582,654,1613,1637]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="12.[134,145,220,238]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="TABLE 3. — External measurements of adult bats captured on Mount Cameroon. Measurements are given as mean ± standard deviation and range." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF4C665DD54C39491C8FFF7FFAB440D7" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" tableUuid="DF4C665DD54C39491C8FFF7FFAB440D7">Table 3</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="502" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="21.[132,775,1662,1845]" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">
HABITATS AND DISTRIBUTION. — This species has been recorded throughout much of West, Central, and East Africa and part of southern Africa (
<bibRefCitation author="Monadjem" box="[300,533,1715,1739]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Monadjem" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" pagination="22102440" refId="ref28187" refString="MONADJEM A., FAHR J., HUTSON A. M., MICKLEBURGH S. &amp; BERGMANS W. 2017 c. - Hipposideros ruber. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2017: e. T 10157 A 22102440. http: // doi. org / 10.2305 / IUCN. UK. 2017 - 2. RLTS. T 10157 A 22102440. en" type="journal article" year="2017" yearSuffix="c">
Monadjem 
<emphasis box="[415,463,1715,1739]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">et al.</emphasis>
2017c
</bibRefCitation>
). According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Happold" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" refId="ref25900" refString="HAPPOLD D. C. D. 1987. - The mammals of Nigeria. Clarendon Press. Oxford, 402 p. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0030605300027708" type="book" year="1987">Happold (1987)</bibRefCitation>
, this species mostly inhabits lowland tropical rain forest, but can also be found in relic and riverine forests in savannah regions where large colonies roost in caves, rocky cavities and abandoned mineshafts.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="502" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[132,776,1870,2027]" lastBlockId="21.[813,1455,215,292]" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">
REMARK. — The species is well known for its variable color phases. The pelage gradually changes from grey or brown just after they early molt to bright russet, as it is oxidized by ammonia fumes within the roosts (
<bibRefCitation author="Fedden &amp; MacLeod" box="[240,495,1949,1973]" firstAuthor="Fedden" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" pagination="175 - 195" refId="ref25479" refString="FEDDEN M. O. &amp; MACLEOD H. L. 1986. - Bat research in western Cameroon in S. N. STUART (ed.), Conservation of Cameroon montane forest. Report of the ICBP Cameroon Montane Forest Survey November 1983 - April 1984. International Council for Bird Preservation, Cambridge: 175 - 195." type="book chapter" year="1986">Fedden &amp; MacLeod 1986</bibRefCitation>
). Recent molecular evidence place 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Noack" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[189,367,1976,2000]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ruber">
<emphasis box="[189,367,1976,2000]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">Hipposideros ruber</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as belonging to the caffer/ruber complex whose taxonomy is still confused (
<bibRefCitation author="Vallo" box="[449,599,2002,2026]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Vallo" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" pagination="193 - 206" refId="ref29896" refString="VALLO P., GUILLEN- SERVENT A., BENDA P., PIRES D. B. &amp; KPUBEK P. 2008. - Variation of mitochondrial DNA in the Hipposideros caffer complex (Chiroptera: Hipposideridae) and its taxonomic implications. Acta Chiropterologica 10: 193 - 206. https: // doi. org / 10.3161 / 150811008 X 414782" type="journal article" year="2008">
Vallo 
<emphasis box="[502,546,2002,2026]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Vallo" box="[610,662,2002,2026]" firstAuthor="Vallo" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" pagination="79 - 88" refId="ref29960" refString="VALLO P., BENDA P., MARTINKOVAN N., KANUCH P., KALKO E. K. V., CERVENY J. &amp; KOUBEK P. 2011. - Morphologically uniform bats Hipposideros aff. ruber (Hipposideridae) exhibit high mitochondrial genetic diversity in southeastern Senegal. Acta Chiropterologica 13: 79 - 88. https: // doi. org / 10.3161 / 150811011 X 578633" type="journal article" year="2011">2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Monadjem" box="[670,916,215,2026]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Monadjem" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" pagination="191 - 207" refId="ref27940" refString="MONADJEM A., RICHARDS L., TAYLOR P. J &amp; STOFFBERG S. 2013. - High diversity of pipistrelloid bats (Vespertilionidae: Hypsugo, Neoromicia, and Pipistrellus) in a West African rainforest with the description of a new species. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 167: 191 - 207." type="journal article" year="2013">
Monadjem 
<emphasis box="[813,860,215,239]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
). Hence while waiting for additional molecular data to resolve the taxonomy of this complex we tentatively include all records from Mount 
<collectingCountry box="[1018,1122,268,292]" name="Cameroon" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Noack" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[1155,1269,268,292]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="502" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ruber">
<emphasis box="[1155,1174,269,292]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">H</emphasis>
. cf. 
<emphasis box="[1216,1269,268,292]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">ruber</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[1269,1273,268,292]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="502">.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
